A dental scientist studying the long-term effects of orthodontic treatments on adolescent patients has gathered data over a period of 5 years. He has represented the data in a 5x5 diagonal matrix, D, where the diagonal elements represent the percentage improvement in orthodontic health each year. The matrix is as follows:

D = [10 0 0 0 0;
     0 15 0 0 0;
     0 0 20 0 0;
     0 0 0 25 0;
     0 0 0 0 30]

Each off-diagonal element is zero, representing no change in the other years.

A patient's orthodontic health score when the study began was 50. Using the diagonal matrix, calculate the patient's orthodontic health score at the end of the 5-year period, assuming that each year's percentage improvement is applied to the previous year's health score.
